  <p class=MsoNormal>&nbsp; </p>
  <p class=MsoNormal align=center style='text-align:center'>&nbsp;</p>
  <p class=MsoNormal align=center style='text-align:center'>&nbsp;</p>
  <p class=MsoNormal align=center style='text-align:center'><b><span
  style='font-size:27.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Arial'>The
  Illinois 4-PEAKS Project</span></b><b><span style='font-size:16.0pt;
  mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Arial'><o:p></o:p></span></b></p>
  <p class=MsoNormal align=center style='text-align:center'><b><span
  style='font-size:16.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Arial'>P</span></b><span
  style='font-size:16.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Arial'>redictable,
  <b>P</b>ower-efficient, <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'>P</b>rogrammable
  <b>P</b>erformance for <o:p></o:p></span></p>
  <p class=MsoNormal align=center style='text-align:center'><b><span
  style='font-size:16.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Arial'>E</span></b><span
  style='font-size:16.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Arial'>merging <b>A</b>pplications
  and wor<b>K</b>load<b>S</b></span></p>
  <p class=MsoNormal align=center style='text-align:center'>&nbsp;</p>
  <p class=MsoNormal align=center style='text-align:center'><br>
  <b>Directed by: <a href="mailto:sadve@cs.uiuc.edu">Sarita V. Adve</a></b></p>
  <p align=center style='text-align:center'><i><a href="http://www.cs.uiuc.edu/">Department
  of Computer Science</a> <br>
  <a href="http://www.uiuc.edu/">University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign</a><br
  clear=all>
  <a href="mailto:rsim@cs.uiuc.edu"><span style='font-style:normal'>rsim@cs.uiuc.edu</span></a></i></p>
  <p class=MsoNormal align=center style='text-align:center'>&nbsp;</p>
  <p class=MsoNormal align=center style='text-align:center'>&nbsp;</p>
  <p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:
  normal'>Background:</b> Multimedia, communications, and network applications
  are an increasingly important workload for a growing number of systems (e.g.,
  future handheld, laptop, and desktop systems, wireless phones and base
  stations, and network switches and routers). As these applications become
  more complex and follow evolving standards, considerations such as
  programmability, upgradability, and portability become more important. As a
  result, general-purpose architectures become increasingly attractive over
  special-purpose designs.</p>
  <p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>&nbsp;</p>
  <p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:
  normal'>Challenges:</b> Our target applications impose many new challenges
  for general-purpose architectures:</p>
  <p class=MsoNormal style='margin-left:.65in;text-align:justify;text-indent:
  -.15in;mso-list:l1 level1 lfo2;tab-stops:list .65in'><![if !supportLists]><span
  style='font-family:Symbol'>·<span style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;
  </span></span><![endif]>They have high <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'>performance
  </b>demands.</p>
  <p class=MsoNormal style='margin-left:.65in;text-align:justify;text-indent:
  -.15in;mso-list:l1 level1 lfo2;tab-stops:list .65in'><![if !supportLists]><span
  style='font-family:Symbol'>·<span style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;
  </span></span><![endif]>They often run on mobile and small form factor
  devices, demanding high <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'>power </b>efficiency
  (including energy and thermal efficiency).</p>
  <p class=MsoNormal style='margin-left:.65in;text-align:justify;text-indent:
  -.15in;mso-list:l1 level1 lfo2;tab-stops:list .65in'><![if !supportLists]><span
  style='font-family:Symbol'>·<span style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;
  </span></span><![endif]>Their real-time nature requires performance to be <b
  style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'>predictable</b>. This is even more
  challenging since they often run on platforms with dynamic changes in the
  availability of resources (e.g., computation, energy, and bandwidth).</p>
  <p class=MsoNormal style='margin-left:.65in;text-align:justify;text-indent:
  -.15in;mso-list:l1 level1 lfo2;tab-stops:list .65in'><![if !supportLists]><span
  style='font-family:Symbol'>·<span style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;
  </span></span><![endif]>The above criteria must be met preserving the
  advantages of <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'>programmability</b> of
  general-purpose processors.</p>
  <p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>&nbsp;</p>
  <p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:
  normal'>Goal: </b>Our goal is to develop architectures that will deliver the
  high <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'>p</b>erformance required for our
  target applications, but in a <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'>p</b>redictable,
  <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'>p</b>ower-efficient, and easy-to-<b
  style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'>p</b>rogram way. We refer to these
  criteria as the 4-P criteria.</p>
  <p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>&nbsp;</p>
  <p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:
  normal'>Opportunities: </b>Because we start with general-purpose
  architectures, we can exploit advances from conventional applications, and conversely,
  many of the techniques we develop are also useful for conventional
  applications. However, our focus on our target application domain allows us
  to exploit some of their unique properties that lead to novel solutions:</p>
  <p class=MsoNormal style='margin-left:.65in;text-align:justify;text-indent:
  -.15in;mso-list:l0 level1 lfo4;tab-stops:list .65in'><![if !supportLists]><span
  style='font-family:Symbol'>·<span style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;
  </span></span><![endif]>Since these applications are <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:
  normal'>real-time</b>, as long as their deadlines are met, we can slow the
  system down to conserve resources.</p>
  <p class=MsoNormal style='margin-left:.65in;text-align:justify;text-indent:
  -.15in;mso-list:l0 level1 lfo4;tab-stops:list .65in'><![if !supportLists]><span
  style='font-family:Symbol'>·<span style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;
  </span></span><![endif]>These applications can often operate at different
  performance levels, enabling a systematic tradeoff between<b
  style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'> user experience vs. resource usage</b>
  (e.g., video quality vs. energy consumption).</p>
  <p class=MsoNormal style='margin-left:.65in;text-align:justify;text-indent:
  -.15in;mso-list:l0 level1 lfo4;tab-stops:list .65in'><![if !supportLists]><span
  style='font-family:Symbol'>·<span style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;
  </span></span><![endif]>Their computations are usually <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:
  normal'>periodic</b> (frame-based) and easier to predict through techniques
  such as profiling, allowing the system to intelligently adapt for predicted
  future demands.</p>
  <p class=MsoNormal style='margin-left:.65in;text-align:justify;text-indent:
  -.15in;mso-list:l0 level1 lfo4;tab-stops:list .65in'><![if !supportLists]><span
  style='font-family:Symbol'>·<span style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;
  </span></span><![endif]>They have significant <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:
  normal'>parallelism</b> at multiple levels, allowing us to exploit on-chip
  multiprocessing and multithreading. </p>
  <p class=MsoNormal style='margin-left:.5in;text-align:justify'>&nbsp;</p>
  <p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:
  normal'>Key Themes: </b>The key themes in our current and ongoing work are:</p>
  <p class=MsoNormal style='margin-left:.65in;text-align:justify;text-indent:
  -.15in;mso-list:l2 level1 lfo6;tab-stops:list .65in'><![if !supportLists]><span
  style='font-family:Symbol'>·<span style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;
  </span></span><![endif]><b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'>Adaptive
  hardware:</b> Changing application requirements and resource availability
  motivate adaptive hardware that can respond to these changes to provide the
  best output quality given the current resources. Our current focus is
  primarily on dynamic energy and temperature management. Our work involves the
  adaptive design of various architectural resources and a coherent framework
  to control multiple adaptive hardware resources to provide a targeted
  performance vs. energy/temperature tradeoff.</p>
  <p class=MsoNormal style='margin-left:.65in;text-align:justify;text-indent:
  -.15in;mso-list:l2 level1 lfo6;tab-stops:list .65in'><![if !supportLists]><span
  style='font-family:Symbol'>·<span style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;
  </span></span><![endif]><b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'>Multithreading
  and multiprocessing:</b> Several of our target applications are inherently multithreaded;
  e.g., a video teleconferencing application consists of several video and
  speech encoders and decoders and each of these has significant parallelism.
  We are investigating on-chip multithreading and multiprocessing to best
  achieve our 4-P criteria.</p>
  <p class=MsoNormal style='margin-left:.65in;text-align:justify;text-indent:
  -.15in;mso-list:l2 level1 lfo6;tab-stops:list .65in'><![if !supportLists]><span
  style='font-family:Symbol'>·<span style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;
  </span></span><![endif]><b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'>Cross-layer
  adaptation:</b> Besides the hardware, we expect other system layers
  (operating system, network, and applications) also to be adaptive. To achieve
  a globally optimal solution, it will be crucial for all the adaptive layers
  in a system to coordinate their adaptations with each other. We are working
  on such a coordinated, cross-layer adaptive system, called <a
  href="http://www.cs.uiuc.edu/grace">GRACE</a>, with researchers in OS,
  networking, and applications.</p>
  <p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>&nbsp;</p>
  <p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>For more specific results and
  ongoing work, please see our <a
  href="http://rsim.cs.uiuc.edu/4-peaks/4-peaks_research.html">research results</a>
  and <a href="http://rsim.cs.uiuc.edu/4-peaks/4-peaks_pubs.html">publications</a>
  pages.</p>
  <p class=MsoNormal><span style='font-family:Verdana'>&nbsp;</span></p>
